column10:
Principia College requires that business partners are contracted with written agreements stating that they abide by federal and state regulations, provide fair and equal wages, and adhere to fair business practices (e.g., no discrimination based on gender, sexual orientation, disability). Principia's Tree Care plan stipulates the methods and practices ensuring environmental protection that building contractors must adhere to when working on Principia campus. Finally, Principia's General Contract Specifications include an ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION section stating, inter alia, that the "Contractor, its employees and agents shall:  
•	Comply strictly with all laws, ordinances, guidelines, recommendations, regulations and restrictions which have been issued by the manufacturer, distributor, or any local, state or federal governmental authority, pertaining to the use, handling, storage and disposal of all Chemical Substances (including without limitation pesticides, herbicides, fungicides, insecticides, fertilizers, petroleum, and all other substances regulated under local, state or federal law, statutes, ordinances, rules and regulations) brought onto Owner's property by Contractor, its employees or agents; 
•	Advise Owner in writing of all conditions arising or resulting from the activities of Contractor, its agents and employees, including without limitation the presence of Chemical Substances on, in or under Owner's property, which may create a risk of harm, injury, or damage of any kind to persons and/or property, including mature trees not approved for harm; 
•	Take all actions reasonably appropriate to eliminate (or where impracticable) reduce, minimize, limit and contain such risk, including without limitation posting of notices, restriction of access to affected areas, and use of alternative Chemical Substances; ..."

column11:
The University of California:
1) cross-matches what the suppliers provide in their Quarterly Business Reviews with information the UC accesses from third-party certifiers;
2) collects Sustainable Purchasing Data from all suppliers on a quarterly basis and has them outline the quantity of their products purchased by UC that are ENERGYSTAR®, EPEAT™, Green Seal™, GreenGuard™, Recycled Content, and WaterSense®; 
3) purchases over 95% of paper (both Multi-Use Office and Rest Room Papers) that has recycled content;
4) purchases only ENERGYSTAR® or EPEAT™ rated office equipment and computing electronics;
5) has take-back clauses for office equipment, large packaging materials, laboratory quality freezers, and toner cartridges; and
6) is in process with converting to energy-efficient laboratory freezers.

All contracts must be in compliance with Air and Water pollution laws (Article 6, Bulletin 56). Food Service business partners (residential, retail, or catering) are extensively covered by UC sustainability policy for sustainable foods with minimum procurement benchmarks for local, organic, and numerous other criteria. Employee training in food selection and preparation is also required, as is patron education, and annual reporting is required for all campuses and medical centers. Sustainable Purchasing is also described in the sustainability policy, and it targets purchasing the best available sustainable products, as well as driving the market through supplier requests for enhanced sustainability features.  Article 22 of the Standard Terms also stipulates that business partners should buy or use Environmentally Preferred Products whenever possible. In addition, contracts negotiated on behalf of the University System are available to general contractors that are constructing or renovating buildings, and building materials, paint and carpet are regularly purchased using these negotiated prices for environmentally preferred products.

Fair hiring is an integral standard at all UC campuses. Equal Opportunity Affirmative Action requirements of business partners is required in Article 12. Protections against forced or compulsory labor are described in Article 17. Health benefits are expected of UC Business partners, and the requirements are described in Article 23. Fair wages are important for UC Business partners, and the expectations and requirements are covered in Articles 24 and 25. All UC projects that are funded by public bonds must adhere to the UC Labor Compliance Program.
Some elements of social responsibility are included in guidelines cited the Sustainable Practices policy. The UC Policy on Sustainable Practices states that the UC supports small businesses, disabled veteran business enterprises, and women-owned businesses. The policy supports both sustainable products purchasing and sustainable business operations.

